AB  - South Africa has historically enjoyed an ability to generate energy cheaply through the use of abundant coal reserves, which has been a key component in the promotion of economic growth. This paper assesses whether it is possible to reconcile economic goals and environmental protection within the nuclear energy sector, whilst meeting the needs of society. Simultaneous economic growth and environmental protection through the use of more efficient technologies have been achieved in the industrialised North, where the policy approach of ecological modernisation (EM) has been followed. Hajer's 'argumentative approach' of understanding how certain policy positions prevail and others are discounted is used as a frame for analysing South Africa's nuclear energy policy to establish the extent to which the policy has the potential to follow an EM approach. The analysis reveals that a policy shift towards nuclear energy shows very little evidence of EM, in spite of nuclear energy scientists' view that the potential exists for the simultaneous goals of growth and environmental efficiency to be realised through advances in environmentally efficient nuclear technology. Interviews with civil society groups emphasised that for an EM-based nuclear energy policy to be successful in meeting a variety of needs, an approach that combines EM with environmental justice will be more appropriate. These findings have important implications for theorising EM in contexts outside of the industrial North.
